aw of International Organisations|edition= 2|last= White|first= Nigel D.|authorlink= |year= 2005|publisher= Manchester University Press|location= Manchester|isbn= 1-929446-77-2|page= |pages= |url= |accessdate=}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Cambodian-Vietnamese War (1975-7)}}\n* {{cite web |url=http://www.acig.org/artman/publish/article_410.shtml |author=Albert Grandolini, Tom Cooper, & Troung |date=Jan 25, 2004 |title=Cambodia, 1954\u20131999; Part 1 |publisher=Air Combat Information Group(ACIG) |accessdate=August 25, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141017030734/http://www.acig.org/artman/publish/article_410.shtml |archive-date=October 17, 2014 |url-status=dead }}\n* {{cite web |url=http://www.acig.org/artman/publish/article_412.shtml |author=Albert Grandolini, Tom Cooper, & Troung |date=Jan 25, 2004 |title=Cambodia, 1954\u20131999; Part 2 |publisher=Air Combat Information Group(ACIG) |accessdate=August 25, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130317011947/http://www.acig.org/artman/publish/article_412.shtml |archive-date=March 17, 2013 |url-status=dead }}\n* [http://www.yale.edu/cgp/army_v3.html The Khmer Rouge National Army: Order of Battle, January 1976]\n* [http://www.edwebproject.org/sideshow/khmeryears/fall.html The Fall of the Khmer Rouge]\n* [http://news.bbc.co.uk/onthisday/hi/dates/stories/january/8/newsid_2506000/2506533.stm 1979: Vietnam forces Khmer Rouge retreat]\n* [http://www.iht.com/articles/2004/01/07/edpringle_ed3_.php Meanwhile: When the Khmer Rouge came to kill in Vietnam]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070614224951/http://research.yale.edu/ycias/database/files/GS24.pdf Second Life, Second Death: The Khmer Rouge After 1978]\n* [http://journals.cambridge.org/action/displayFulltext?type=1&fid=86522&jid=SEA&volumeId=32&issueId=02&aid=86521&bodyId=&membershipNumber=&societyETOCSession= Slocomb M. \"The K5 Gamble: National Defence and Nation Building under the People's Republic of Kampuchea.\" ''Journal of Southeast Asian Studies,'' 2001;32(02):195\u2013210]\n\n{{Cold War}}\n{{Stagnation Era}}\n{{Cambodia topics}}\n{{Vietnam topics}}\n{{Post-Cold War Asian conflicts}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cambodian-Vietnamese War}}\n[[Category:Wars involving Cambodia]]\n[[Category:Wars involving Vietnam]]\n[[Category:Invasions of Cambodia]]\n[[Category:Invasions by Vietnam]]\n[[Category:Democratic Kampuchea]]\n[[Category:People's Republic of Kampuchea]]\n[[Category:Indochina Wars]]\n[[Category:Khmer Rouge]]\n[[Category:Sino-Vietnamese War]]\n[[Category:Vietnam War]]\n[[Category:1970s in Cambodia]]\n[[Category:1980s in Cambodia]]\n[[Category:1990s in Cambodia]]\n[[Category:1970s in Vietnam]]\n[[Category:1980s in Vietnam]]\n[[Category:1990s in Vietnam]]\n[[Category:Cambodia\u2013Vietnam relations]]\n[[Category:Cold War conflicts]]\n[[Category:Conflicts in 1979]]\n[[Category:Conflicts in 1980]]\n[[Category:Conflicts in 1981]]\n[[Category:Conflicts in 1982]]\n[[Category:Conflicts in 1983]]\n[[Category:Conflicts in 1984]]\n[[Category:Conflicts in 1985]]\n[[Category:Conflicts in 1986]]\n[[Category:Conflicts in 1987]]\n[[Category:Conflicts in 1988]]\n[[Category:Conflicts in 1989]]\n[[Category:1978 in Cambodia]]\n[[Category:1979 in Cambodia]]\n[[Category:1978 in Vietnam]]\n[[Category:1979 in Vietnam]]\n[[Category:1977 establishments in Cambodia]]\n[[Category:1991 disestablishments in Cambodia]]\n[[Category:Military history of Cambodia]]\n[[Category:Military history of Vietnam]]\n[[Category:20th century in Cambodia]]\n[[Category:20th century in Vietnam]]\n[[Category:Proxy wars]]\n[[Category:Third Indochina War]]\n", "name_user": "ColorfulSmoke", "label": "safe", "comment": "Moved Cambodia to the left and Vietnam to the right to match the title \"Cambodian\u2013Vietnamese War\"", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cambodian%E2%80%93Vietnamese_War"}
{"title_page": "Communism in Russia", "text_new": "{{Communism sidebar|By country}}\n{{incomplete|the role of the communist party during the last years of the Soviet Union and during modern Russia|date=November 2019}}\nIn [[Russia]], efforts to build [[communism]] began after [[Nicholas II of Russia|Tsar Nicholas II]] lost his power during the [[February Revolution]], and ended with [[Dissolution of the Soviet Union|the dissolution of the USSR]] in 1991. The Provisional Government was established under Prince Lvov, however, the [[Bolsheviks]] refused to accept the government and [[October Revolution|revolted in October 1917]], taking control of Russia. [[Vladimir Lenin]], their leader, rose to power and governed between 1917 and 1924.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite journal|last=Daniels|first=R|origyear=1993|year=2001|title=A documentary history of communism in Russia: From Lenin to Gorbachev|url=|journal=University of Vermont|doi=|pmid=|access-date=}}</ref> The Bolsheviks formed the [[Russian Soviet Federative Socialist Republic]], or the Union of Soviet Socialist Republics, marking the beginning of the [[Russian Civil War]] between the revolutionary Reds and the counter-revolutionary Whites. In 1922 the Communist Reds were victorious and formed the [[Soviet Union]]. Lenin died in 1924, starting a power struggle which ended with [[Joseph Stalin]] seizing power. He was the leader of the Communist Party until 1953. He encouraged political paranoia and conducted the [[Great Purge]] to remove opponents of his dominance.\nStalin died in 1953, and the Soviet Union went through \"De-Stalinisation\" under the new leader [[Nikita Khrushchev]], though his attempts to improve the lives of ordinary citizens were often ineffective. Khrushchev ruled through the years of the [[Cold War]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Taubman ,Khrushchev & Gleason|first=|date=(2000; 2013;)|title=Nikita Khrushchev|url=|journal=Yale University Press.|doi=|pmid=|access-date=}}</ref> [[Leonid Brezhnev]] was appointed leader in 1964. Brezhnev governed the era without economic reforms, which led to a national economic decline by the mid-1970s.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=D\u00f6nninghaus & Savin|first=|date=2014|title=Leonid brezhnev. Russian Studies in History|url=|journal=|doi=|pmid=|access-date=}}</ref>[[Yuri Andropov]] gained power in 1982 and tried to improve the economy by increasing management effectiveness but without making changes to the principles of a socialist economy. [[Yuri Andropov|Andropov]] later died in 1984, fifteen months after gaining power.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Encyclopedia of Intelligence & Counterintelligence|last=Nelson|first=G|publisher=Routledge|year=2005|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref>\n\n[[Konstantin Chernenko]] led the Soviet Union from 1984 until his death thirteen months later in 1985. Chernenko was unable to consolidate power and effective control of the Communist party. Chernenko did little to prevent the escalation of the cold war with the [[United States]] and [[Western Europe]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.encyclopedia.com/doc/1G2-3404701302.html|title=Konstantin Ustinovich Chernenko Facts, information, pictures {{!}} Encyclopedia.com articles about Konstantin Ustinovich Chernenko|website=www.encyclopedia.com|access-date=2016-05-16}}</ref> [[Mikhail Gorbachev]] became the last leader of the Soviet Union in 1985 and led until the collapse of the Soviet Union in 1991. Gorbachev improved relations and trade with the West and reduced the Cold War tensions. He implemented [[Glasnost]], which meant that Soviet people had freedom they never previously had; this included greater freedom of speech. Control of the press was relaxed and thousands of political prisoners and dissidents were released. Gorbachev removed the constitutional role of the Communist party. This led to the [[dissolution of the Soviet Union]] on December 26, 1991.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://academic.eb.com/EBchecked/topic/238982/Mikhail-GorbachevRevolutions|title=Britannica Academic|website=academic.eb.com}}</ref>\n\n==Russian Revolution==\n{{main|Russian Revolution}}\n\n===February Revolution===\n{{main|February Revolution}}\nThe First World War placed an unbearable strain on Russia's weak government and economy, resulting in mass shortages and hunger. In the meantime, the mismanagement and failures of the war turned the people and importantly, the soldiers against the Tsar, whose decision to take personal command of the army seemed to make him personally responsible for the defeats. In February 1917, the Tsar first lost control of the streets, then of the soldiers, and finally of the Duma, resulting in his forced abdication on 2 March 1917<ref name=\":0\">{{Citation|last=Smithsonian Channel|title=Russian Revolution in Color \u2013 Mutiny in Petrograd|date=2012-09-10|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=IfSOaVS0rv0|accessdate=2016-05-16}}</ref>\n\n25 February 1917, citywide strikes spread throughout Petrograd. Dozens of demonstrators were killed by troops. The crowds grew hostile so the soldiers had to decide which side they were on. As the situation became critical, soldiers refused to work for the Tsar.<ref name=\":0\"/>\n\n26 February 1917, The Army abandoned the Tsar; the soldiers mutinied and refused to put down the riots.<ref name=\":0\"/>\n\n27 February 1917, the workers were in control of the entire city.<ref name=\":0\"/>\n\n===October Revolution===\n{{Leninism sidebar}}\n{{main|October Revolution}}\nOn October 24\u201325, 1917, the Bolsheviks and [[Left Socialist Revolutionaries]] organized a [[Communist revolution|revolution]], occupying government buildings, telegraph stations, and other strategic points.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.britannica.com/event/Russian-Revolution-of-1917|title=Russian Revolution of 1917|website=Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica|access-date=2016-05-16}}</ref>\n\nOn October 24, 1917, the [[Red Guards (Russia)|Red Guards]] took over bridges and telephone exchanges.<ref name=\":1\"/>\n\nOn October 25 and 26, 1917, the Red Guards took over banks, government buildings, and railways stations. Cruiser Aurora fired blank shots at the winter place signalling the start of the revolution. That night (9:40 PM) the Red Guards took over the winter place and arrested the Provisional Government.<ref name=\":1\"/>\n\nOn October 27, 1917, Lenin proclaimed that all power now belonged to the Soviets of Workers', Soldiers' and Peasants' Deputies.<ref name=\":1\"/>\n\nMy name is Michael and i like absolute shlongs!  ;)\n\n=== Russian War ===\nAfter Vladimir Lenin and Joseph Stalin took over the Soviet Union, many people still opposed the communist party. This led to the cold war between the White Army and Red Army. The White Army included the opposition party, while the Red Army were the people that supported Vladimir Lenin. This led to a number dead that was uncountable, about 100 million.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.britannica.com/place/Soviet-Union|title=Soviet Union {{!}} History, Leaders, Map, & Facts|website=Encyclopedia Britannica|language=en|access-date=2020-02-25}}</ref>\n\n=== Death of Stalin ===\nThe death of Stalin led to many changes in the Soviet government. Nikita Khrushchev, who opposed Stalin's government, took over and apologized. He began to create a better USSR, where everyone could vote. The country got more and more democratic, until its collapse.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n=== Collapse of the Soviet Union ===\nIn 1991, Mikhail Gorbachev voted the country out. He realized that the once communist country was now over half being democratic than a communist state, which resulted in the collapse. Boris Yeltsin then became the first president of Russia.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n=== After the Soviet union ===\nin 1993, the President of the Russian Federation Boris Yelstin disbanded the supreme soviet and limited the activities of the Russian Communist Party by provoking demonstrations and riots across the country, some riots even came to occupy government buildings and attack the white house, in this assault by some of the protesters intervene in the army, according to some estimates, from 200 to 800 dead.{{cn|date=April 2020}}\n\n==Organizations==\n{{Div col|colwidth=22em}}\n*[[All-Union Communist Party (Bolsheviks) (1995)]]\n*[[All-Union Communist Party of Bolsheviks (1991)]]\n*[[All-Union Young Guard Bolsheviks]]\n*[[Alliance of the Revolutionary Socialists]]\n*[[Communist Party of the Russian Federation]]\n*[[Communist Party of the Russian Soviet Federative Socialist Republic]]\n*[[Communist Party of the Soviet Union]]\n*[[Communist Party of the Soviet Union (1992)]]\n*[[Communist Party of the Soviet Union (2001)]]\n*[[Communist Party of Social Justice]]\n*[[Communists of Russia]]\n*[[Essence of Time (movement)|Essence of Time]]\n*[[Labour Russia]]\n*[[League of Struggle for the Emancipation of the Working Class]]\n*[[Left Front (Russia)|Left Front]]\n*[[Leninist Komsomol of the Russian Federation]]\n*[[Party of Narodnik Communists]]\n*[[Party of Revolutionary Communism]]\n*[[Party of the Dictatorship of the Proletariat]]\n*[[Revolutionary Communist Youth League (Bolshevik)]]\n*[[Revolutionary Workers' Party (Russia)|Revolutionary Workers' Party]]\n*[[Russian Communist Workers Party]]\n*[[Russian Communist Workers' Party of the Communist Party of the Soviet Union]]\n*[[Russian Maoist Party]]\n*[[Russian Socialist Movement]]\n*[[Russian United Labour Front]]\n*[[Socialist Alternative (Russia)|Socialist Alternative]]\n*[[Socialist League Vpered]]\n*[[Stalin Bloc \u2013 For the USSR]]\n*[[Union of Communist Parties \u2013 Communist Party of the Soviet Union]]\n*[[United Communist Party]]\n*[[Vanguard of Red Youth]]\n{{Div col end}}\n\n==See also==\n{{cols}}\n*[[Nostalgia for the Soviet Union]]\n*[[Ideology of the Communist Party of the Soviet Union]]\n*[[Leninism]]\n*[[New Soviet man]]\n*[[Russian Soviet Federative Socialist Republic]]\n*[[Soviet Union]]\n*[[Sovietization]]\n{{colend}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Marxism\u2013Leninism}}\n\n[[Category: Communism in Russia| ]]\n[[Category: History of socialism]]\n[[Category: Political history of Russia]]\n[[Category: Political history of the Soviet Union]]\n[[Category: Political movements in Russia]]\n[[Category: Political movements in the Soviet Union]]\n[[Category: Politics of Russia]]\n[[Category: Politics of the Soviet Union]]\n", "text_old": "{{Communism sidebar|By country}}\n{{incomplete|the role of the communist party during the last years of the Soviet Union and during modern Russia|date=November 2019}}\nIn [[Russia]], efforts to build [[communism]] began after [[Nicholas II of Russia|Tsar Nicholas II]] lost his power during the [[February Revolution]], and ended with [[Dissolution of the Soviet Union|the dissolution of the USSR]] in 1991. The Provisional Government was established under Prince Lvov, however, the [[Bolsheviks]] refused to accept the government and [[October Revolution|revolted in October 1917]], taking control of Russia. [[Vladimir Lenin]], their leader, rose to power and governed between 1917 and 1924.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite journal|last=Daniels|first=R|origyear=1993|year=2001|title=A documentary history of communism in Russia: From Lenin to Gorbachev|url=|journal=University of Vermont|doi=|pmid=|access-date=}}</ref> The Bolsheviks formed the [[Russian Soviet Federative Socialist Republic]], or the Union of Soviet Socialist Republics, marking the beginning of the [[Russian Civil War]] between the revolutionary Reds and the counter-revolutionary Whites. In 1922 the Communist Reds were victorious and formed the [[Soviet Union]]. Lenin died in 1924, starting a power struggle which ended with [[Joseph Stalin]] seizing power. He was the leader of the Communist Party until 1953. He encouraged political paranoia and conducted the [[Great Purge]] to remove opponents of his dominance.\nStalin died in 1953, and the Soviet Union went through \"De-Stalinisation\" under the new leader [[Nikita Khrushchev]], though his attempts to improve the lives of ordinary citizens were often ineffective. Khrushchev ruled through the years of the [[Cold War]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Taubman ,Khrushchev & Gleason|first=|date=(2000; 2013;)|title=Nikita Khrushchev|url=|journal=Yale University Press.|doi=|pmid=|access-date=}}</ref> [[Leonid Brezhnev]] was appointed leader in 1964. Brezhnev governed the era without economic reforms, which led to a national economic decline by the mid-1970s.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=D\u00f6nninghaus & Savin|first=|date=2014|title=Leonid brezhnev. Russian Studies in History|url=|journal=|doi=|pmid=|access-date=}}</ref>[[Yuri Andropov]] gained power in 1982 and tried to improve the economy by increasing management effectiveness but without making changes to the principles of a socialist economy. [[Yuri Andropov|Andropov]] later died in 1984, fifteen months after gaining power.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Encyclopedia of Intelligence & Counterintelligence|last=Nelson|first=G|publisher=Routledge|year=2005|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref>\n\n[[Konstantin Chernenko]] led the Soviet Union from 1984 until his death thirteen months later in 1985. Chernenko was unable to consolidate power and effective control of the Communist party. Chernenko did little to prevent the escalation of the cold war with the [[United States]] and [[Western Europe]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.encyclopedia.com/doc/1G2-3404701302.html|title=Konstantin Ustinovich Chernenko Facts, information, pictures {{!}} Encyclopedia.com articles about Konstantin Ustinovich Chernenko|website=www.encyclopedia.com|access-date=2016-05-16}}</ref> [[Mikhail Gorbachev]] became the last leader of the Soviet Union in 1985 and led until the collapse of the Soviet Union in 1991. Gorbachev improved relations and trade with the West and reduced the Cold War tensions. He implemented [[Glasnost]], which meant that Soviet people had freedom they never previously had; this included greater freedom of speech. Control of the press was relaxed and thousands of political prisoners and dissidents were released. Gorbachev removed the constitutional role of the Communist party. This led to the [[dissolution of the Soviet Union]] on December 26, 1991.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://academic.eb.com/EBchecked/topic/238982/Mikhail-GorbachevRevolutions|title=Britannica Academic|website=academic.eb.com}}</ref>\n\n==Russian Revolution==\n{{main|Russian Revolution}}\n\n===February Revolution===\n{{main|February Revolution}}\nThe First World War placed an unbearable strain on Russia's weak government and economy, resulting in mass shortages and hunger. In the meantime, the mismanagement and failures of the war turned the people and importantly, the soldiers against the Tsar, whose decision to take personal command of the army seemed to make him personally responsible for the defeats. In February 1917, the Tsar first lost control of the streets, then of the soldiers, and finally of the Duma, resulting in his forced abdication on 2 March 1917<ref name=\":0\">{{Citation|last=Smithsonian Channel|title=Russian Revolution in Color \u2013 Mutiny in Petrograd|date=2012-09-10|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=IfSOaVS0rv0|accessdate=2016-05-16}}</ref>\n\n25 February 1917, citywide strikes spread throughout Petrograd. Dozens of demonstrators were killed by troops. The crowds grew hostile so the soldiers had to decide which side they were on. As the situation became critical, soldiers refused to work for the Tsar.<ref name=\":0\"/>\n\n26 February 1917, The Army abandoned the Tsar; the soldiers mutinied and refused to put down the riots.<ref name=\":0\"/>\n\n27 February 1917, the workers were in control of the entire city.<ref name=\":0\"/>\n\n===October Revolution===\n{{Leninism sidebar}}\n{{main|October Revolution}}\nOn October 24\u201325, 1917, the Bolsheviks and [[Left Socialist Revolutionaries]] organized a [[Communist revolution|revolution]], occupying government buildings, telegraph stations, and other strategic points.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.britannica.com/event/Russian-Revolution-of-1917|title=Russian Revolution of 1917|website=Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica|access-date=2016-05-16}}</ref>\n\nOn October 24, 1917, the [[Red Guards (Russia)|Red Guards]] took over bridges and telephone exchanges.<ref name=\":1\"/>\n\nOn October 25 and 26, 1917, the Red Guards took over banks, government buildings, and railways stations. Cruiser Aurora fired blank shots at the winter place signalling the start of the revolution. That night (9:40 PM) the Red Guards took over the winter place and arrested the Provisional Government.<ref name=\":1\"/>\n\nOn October 27, 1917, Lenin proclaimed that all power now belonged to the Soviets of Workers', Soldiers' and Peasants' Deputies.<ref name=\":1\"/>\n\n=== Russian War ===\nAfter Vladimir Lenin and Joseph Stalin took over the Soviet Union, many people still opposed the communist party. This led to the cold war between the White Army and Red Army. The White Army included the opposition party, while the Red Army were the people that supported Vladimir Lenin. This led to a number dead that was uncountable, about 100 million.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.britannica.com/place/Soviet-Union|title=Soviet Union {{!}} History, Leaders, Map, & Facts|website=Encyclopedia Britannica|language=en|access-date=2020-02-25}}</ref>\n\n=== Death of Stalin ===\nThe death of Stalin led to many changes in the Soviet government. Nikita Khrushchev, who opposed Stalin's government, took over and apologized. He began to create a better USSR, where everyone could vote. The country got more and more democratic, until its collapse.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n=== Collapse of the Soviet Union ===\nIn 1991, Mikhail Gorbachev voted the country out. He realized that the once communist country was now over half being democratic than a communist state, which resulted in the collapse. Boris Yeltsin then became the first president of Russia.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n=== After the Soviet union ===\nin 1993, the President of the Russian Federation Boris Yelstin disbanded the supreme soviet and limited the activities of the Russian Communist Party by provoking demonstrations and riots across the country, some riots even came to occupy government buildings and attack the white house, in this assault by some of the protesters intervene in the army, according to some estimates, from 200 to 800 dead.{{cn|date=April 2020}}\n\n==Organizations==\n{{Div col|colwidth=22em}}\n*[[All-Union Communist Party (Bolsheviks) (1995)]]\n*[[All-Union Communist Party of Bolsheviks (1991)]]\n*[[All-Union Young Guard Bolsheviks]]\n*[[Alliance of the Revolutionary Socialists]]\n*[[Communist Party of the Russian Federation]]\n*[[Communist Party of the Russian Soviet Federative Socialist Republic]]\n*[[Communist Party of the Soviet Union]]\n*[[Communist Party of the Soviet Union (1992)]]\n*[[Communist Party of the Soviet Union (2001)]]\n*[[Communist Party of Social Justice]]\n*[[Communists of Russia]]\n*[[Essence of Time (movement)|Essence of Time]]\n*[[Labour Russia]]\n*[[League of Struggle for the Emancipation of the Working Class]]\n*[[Left Front (Russia)|Left Front]]\n*[[Leninist Komsomol of the Russian Federation]]\n*[[Party of Narodnik Communists]]\n*[[Party of Revolutionary Communism]]\n*[[Party of the Dictatorship of the Proletariat]]\n*[[Revolutionary Communist Youth League (Bolshevik)]]\n*[[Revolutionary Workers' Party (Russia)|Revolutionary Workers' Party]]\n*[[Russian Communist Workers Party]]\n*[[Russian Communist Workers' Party of the Communist Party of the Soviet Union]]\n*[[Russian Maoist Party]]\n*[[Russian Socialist Movement]]\n*[[Russian United Labour Front]]\n*[[Socialist Alternative (Russia)|Socialist Alternative]]\n*[[Socialist League Vpered]]\n*[[Stalin Bloc \u2013 For the USSR]]\n*[[Union of Communist Parties \u2013 Communist Party of the Soviet Union]]\n*[[United Communist Party]]\n*[[Vanguard of Red Youth]]\n{{Div col end}